00:04:22.120 --> 00:04:24.880
Good afternoon. My name is William Bowers.

75
00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:28.940
I am a undergraduate student and university undergraduate research fellow

76
00:04:29.060 --> 00:04:32.710
at Johns Hopkins University. On behalf of my peers in the

77
00:04:32.710 --> 00:04:36.620
molecular oncology lab at the Sidney Kimmel Comprehensive Cancer Center,

78
00:04:37.160 --> 00:04:40.820
I'm delighted to present to you our study entitled "Serial Plasma

79
00:04:40.900 --> 00:04:44.490
Comprehensive Genomic Profiling Detects Therapy Resistance and Guides

80
00:04:44.580 --> 00:04:47.120
Management of Metastatic Non-Small Cell Lung Cancer."

81
00:04:48.620 --> 00:04:50.160
I have no financial disclosures.

82
00:04:51.780 --> 00:04:55.740
Comprehensive genomic profiling of non-small cell lung cancer tumors has

83
00:04:55.800 --> 00:04:59.719
unraveled oncogene dependencies and therapeutic vulnerabilities that have been

84
00:04:59.780 --> 00:05:02.920
translated into new treatment strategies with a clear survival

85
00:05:02.930 --> 00:05:06.640
benefit. To this end, plasma comprehensive genomic

86
00:05:06.660 --> 00:05:10.640
profiling offers a minimally invasive, cost-effective, and rapid

87
00:05:10.740 --> 00:05:14.390
turnaround approach to match patients to genotype-targeted therapies,

88
00:05:14.720 --> 00:05:18.670
monitor response to therapy, and capture drivers of therapy resistance,

89
00:05:19.260 --> 00:05:21.080
enabling treatment optimization.

90
00:05:21.800 --> 00:05:24.980
But still, the precise clinical utility of serial

91
00:05:25.020 --> 00:05:28.820
PCGP remains insufficiently studied outside of

92
00:05:28.860 --> 00:05:32.000
controlled trials in real-world institutional cohorts.

93
00:05:34.140 --> 00:05:37.520
Using EGFR-driven non-small cell lung cancer as a representative

94
00:05:37.560 --> 00:05:41.520
example, retrospective liquid biopsy analyses were used to

95
00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:45.460
evaluate mechanisms of acquired resistance to osimertnib in the FLORA

96
00:05:45.520 --> 00:05:47.700
trial, with osimertnib representing

97
00:05:47.780 --> 00:05:51.692
the-Standard treatment recommended

98
00:05:51.752 --> 00:05:55.512
care as first-line therapy in patients with non-small cell lung cancer harboring

99
00:05:55.552 --> 00:05:57.851
canonical EGFR activating alterations.

100
00:05:58.572 --> 00:06:02.242
And the most commonly detected mechanism of resistance was MET amplification,

101
00:06:02.392 --> 00:06:04.752
followed by secondary EGFR alterations.

102
00:06:05.272 --> 00:06:09.002
And in addition to patients with single acquired resistance mechanisms, several

103
00:06:09.112 --> 00:06:13.072
patients had multiple resistance mechanisms, including co-mutations in genes

104
00:06:13.492 --> 00:06:17.432
involved in cancer hallmarks such as cell cycle control and in the MAP kinase

105
00:06:17.532 --> 00:06:21.442
pathway. And this resistance landscape differs from that associated with

106
00:06:21.572 --> 00:06:25.472
first and second generation EGFR TKIs, which is really driven

107
00:06:25.552 --> 00:06:28.932
by EGFR T790M alterations, and is followed

108
00:06:29.012 --> 00:06:32.752
secondarily by MET amplification, and by CDK6

109
00:06:32.792 --> 00:06:36.222
amplification as well. And so this study, and

110
00:06:36.372 --> 00:06:40.112
others jointly indicate that mechanisms of acquired resistance

111
00:06:40.312 --> 00:06:44.072
to genotype-targeted therapies in non-small cell lung cancer are driven by the

112
00:06:44.132 --> 00:06:47.892
selective pressure of TKIs, which can vary based on the specific

113
00:06:47.972 --> 00:06:49.932
drug and how these drugs are sequenced.

114
00:06:51.252 --> 00:06:55.072
And so our main goal was to understand the clinical utility of serial

115
00:06:55.092 --> 00:06:58.962
PCGP in a real-world institutional cohort for informing

116
00:06:59.052 --> 00:07:02.492
precision oncology interventions and for characterizing drivers of therapy

117
00:07:02.532 --> 00:07:06.012
resistance based on the targeted therapy used and whether it was used as

118
00:07:06.152 --> 00:07:07.872
first-line or later-line treatment.

119
00:07:08.852 --> 00:07:12.592
To that end, we conducted a retrospective study of 718 patients with

120
00:07:12.612 --> 00:07:15.812
non-small cell lung cancer who had at least one instance of liquid

121
00:07:15.912 --> 00:07:19.382
biopsy and were managed at our institution between 2015 and

122
00:07:19.532 --> 00:07:20.231
2022.

123
00:07:21.222 --> 00:07:25.142
The detailed cohort characteristics are shown in the table on the right, and

124
00:07:25.192 --> 00:07:28.812
among 214 patients with EGFR mutant non-small cell lung cancer,

125
00:07:29.572 --> 00:07:33.552
42% were administered first-line osimertnib, and the remaining 58% were

126
00:07:33.592 --> 00:07:37.552
treated with a first or second-generation EGFR TKI, which really

127
00:07:37.572 --> 00:07:40.792
represents the evolving treatment landscape during the study duration.

128
00:07:41.712 --> 00:07:45.382
We leveraged standard workflows belonging to the Johns Hopkins Precision

129
00:07:45.472 --> 00:07:49.282
Medicine Analytics Platform and Lung Cancer Precision Medicine Center of

130
00:07:49.372 --> 00:07:52.732
Excellence, which jointly enabled multi-source data

131
00:07:52.812 --> 00:07:56.732
integration for thoracic cancer cohorts within a precision oncology

132
00:07:56.812 --> 00:07:57.261
framework.

133
00:07:58.231 --> 00:08:02.172
Variant calls from fixed gene panel hybrid capture next-generation sequencing

134
00:08:02.612 --> 00:08:06.372
assays, Guardant 360 and Guardant 360X, were programmatically

135
00:08:06.412 --> 00:08:10.372
retrieved, and these assays were performed as part of standard of care management.

136
00:08:10.972 --> 00:08:14.952
We also programmatically retrieved tissue next-generation sequencing data, which

137
00:08:14.972 --> 00:08:18.862
comprised a range of CLIA-approved assays, again, used for routine

138
00:08:18.972 --> 00:08:21.542
comprehensive genomic profiling in the clinical setting.

139
00:08:22.992 --> 00:08:26.732
Genomic alterations were characterized based on the AMP-ASCO-CAP joint

140
00:08:26.892 --> 00:08:30.382
guidelines, and Tier 1 genomic alterations were classified as

141
00:08:30.472 --> 00:08:34.413
actionable based on FDA approvals at the time of review, which

142
00:08:34.452 --> 00:08:35.812
was in May 2024.

143
00:08:37.372 --> 00:08:41.352
Across the entire study cohort, 37% of patients had an actionable

144
00:08:41.413 --> 00:08:45.212
alteration on their first instance of plasma genomic profiling.

145
00:08:45.232 --> 00:08:48.852
And in the 427 patients with a liquid biopsy in the treatment-naive

146
00:08:48.932 --> 00:08:52.712
setting, 36% of these patients had an alteration

147
00:08:52.752 --> 00:08:56.312
captured by a liquid biopsy that was associated with an FDA-approved

148
00:08:56.332 --> 00:08:57.801
genotype-matched targeted therapy.

149
00:08:58.182 --> 00:09:01.102
And the breakdown of these alterations is shown in the pie chart here, and you can

150
00:09:01.212 --> 00:09:05.182
see that they most commonly occurred in EGFR and KRAS, which is what we expected.

151
00:09:05.732 --> 00:09:09.712
And ultimately, 22% of these treatment-naive patients initiated a

152
00:09:09.732 --> 00:09:13.712
PCGP-matched targeted therapy within 30 days of the liquid biopsy

153
00:09:13.772 --> 00:09:14.292
results.

154
00:09:15.892 --> 00:09:19.292
We then wanted to understand what was the relationship between ctDNA

155
00:09:19.332 --> 00:09:23.072
detectability and overall survival in the treatment-naive

156
00:09:23.132 --> 00:09:26.732
subset. And as we expected, patients with undetectable

157
00:09:26.792 --> 00:09:30.652
ctDNA had significantly better overall survival than those with one

158
00:09:30.712 --> 00:09:34.632
to two mutations or three or more mutations detected by PCGP.

159
00:09:35.272 --> 00:09:38.832
And importantly, patients who received a genotype-targeted therapy based on an

160
00:09:38.912 --> 00:09:42.222
actionable alteration identified by PCGP had

161
00:09:42.232 --> 00:09:46.012
significantly better overall survival compared to those who did not.

162
00:09:46.021 --> 00:09:49.852
And these findings jointly indicate that alterations captured by liquid biopsy are

163
00:09:49.912 --> 00:09:53.712
clinically informative, even for non-actionable alterations whose

164
00:09:53.752 --> 00:09:57.292
density is still offering valuable insight into patient survival.

165
00:09:57.301 --> 00:10:00.972
And when liquid biopsy is capturing actionable alterations, it's directly

166
00:10:01.012 --> 00:10:04.592
enhancing clinical outcomes for patients with non-small cell lung cancer

167
00:10:04.972 --> 00:10:08.652
by enabling timely matching to highly effective genotype-targeted therapies.

168
00:10:10.592 --> 00:10:14.252
We then wanted to investigate in which clinical scenarios PCGP was

169
00:10:14.312 --> 00:10:18.222
uniquely informing clinical management, in addition to the information that

170
00:10:18.232 --> 00:10:21.112
we're gleaning from tissue next-generation sequencing in these patients.

171
00:10:21.772 --> 00:10:25.232
And so across first, second, and third instance of plasma genotyping,

172
00:10:25.772 --> 00:10:29.532
liquid biopsy was uniquely informative in 84, nine, and three cases

173
00:10:29.612 --> 00:10:33.092
respectively, which totaled 13% of the total study cohort.

174
00:10:33.582 --> 00:10:36.692
And this most commonly occurred when tissue testing was clinically

175
00:10:36.732 --> 00:10:40.432
infeasible. But we also saw liquid biopsy uniquely guiding

176
00:10:40.472 --> 00:10:43.872
patient management by improving on turnaround time compared to tissue

177
00:10:43.892 --> 00:10:47.862
next-generation sequencing by detecting mutations not found in

178
00:10:47.892 --> 00:10:51.612
tissue-matched samples that were matched to FDA-approved targeted therapies,

179
00:10:52.592 --> 00:10:56.492
by indicating the absence of acquired resistance alterations, and also

180
00:10:56.532 --> 00:11:00.372
by detecting mutations not found in tissue-matched samples that met clinical

181
00:11:00.412 --> 00:11:04.152
trial criteria. And so these findings characterize, or underscore

182
00:11:04.212 --> 00:11:07.552
previously characterized advantages of liquid biopsy in a real-world

183
00:11:07.652 --> 00:11:11.522
institutional setting, and also underscore that plasma genomic profiling can

184
00:11:11.592 --> 00:11:15.062
offer unique clinical benefit to patients with non-small cell lung cancer

185
00:11:15.372 --> 00:11:18.282
beyond the information we're getting from tissue genotyping.

186
00:11:19.932 --> 00:11:23.522
Among the 214 patients with EGFR-driven non-small cell lung cancer,

187
00:11:23.912 --> 00:11:27.342
liquid biopsy was especially informative and uniquely guided management in

188
00:11:27.492 --> 00:11:31.112
28% of cases versus 13% of the general

189
00:11:31.372 --> 00:11:34.992
study population. And at the time of progression on EGFR TKI

190
00:11:35.272 --> 00:11:39.092
therapy, 22% of these patients had actionable alterations

191
00:11:39.312 --> 00:11:43.072
captured by plasma genomic profiling, of which 58% of these

192
00:11:43.112 --> 00:11:46.922
patients were matched to a genotype-targeted therapy based on those findings.

193
00:11:47.282 --> 00:11:50.832
And we're showing in the swimmer's plot here 12 representative cases of patients

194
00:11:50.852 --> 00:11:54.772
with EGFR mutant non-small cell lung cancer whose management was guided

195
00:11:54.812 --> 00:11:58.722
by serial PCGP. And you can appreciate the liquid biopsy-informed

196
00:11:58.832 --> 00:12:02.432
therapy switches shown as these black boxes in the swimmer's plot, which were

197
00:12:02.472 --> 00:12:06.152
predominantly driven by acquired EGFR T790M

198
00:12:06.192 --> 00:12:10.172
alterations, EGFR C797S alterations, as

199
00:12:10.232 --> 00:12:12.092
well as MET amplifications and BRAF

200
00:12:12.132 --> 00:12:15.592
alterations.We then wanted to

201
00:12:15.652 --> 00:12:19.172
understand the landscape of on- and off-target putative resistance

202
00:12:19.252 --> 00:12:23.072
mutations by EGFR TKI treatment line for TKIs of

203
00:12:23.092 --> 00:12:26.692
various types, including osimertnib and first and second-generation EGFR

204
00:12:26.812 --> 00:12:30.682
TKIs that were captured by plasma germline profiling in

205
00:12:30.752 --> 00:12:33.852
this EGFR mutant patient subpopulation.

206
00:12:33.872 --> 00:12:37.502
So in the landscape plot here, each patient represents a column, and patients are

207
00:12:37.532 --> 00:12:41.242
clustered according to EGFR TKI line of therapy, starting with

208
00:12:41.272 --> 00:12:45.252
TKI-naive on the left and proceeding to post-third-line EGFR

209
00:12:45.312 --> 00:12:49.112
TKI therapy on the right. And EGFR primary and secondary

210
00:12:49.172 --> 00:12:52.492
alterations are shown on the top, and the remaining alterations are clustered

211
00:12:53.052 --> 00:12:55.132
according to cancer hallmark and pathway.

212
00:12:55.902 --> 00:12:59.532
And so in terms of on-target resistance, as we expected, we saw EGFR

213
00:12:59.572 --> 00:13:03.222
T790M alterations emerging after first and second-generation

214
00:13:03.252 --> 00:13:06.812
TKI therapy versus EGFR C797S and

215
00:13:06.892 --> 00:13:09.272
compound mutations being acquired after first-line

216
00:13:09.392 --> 00:13:13.012
osimertnib. EGFR primary activating mutations

217
00:13:13.132 --> 00:13:16.672
commonly co-occurred with EGFR amplifications in the

218
00:13:16.712 --> 00:13:20.592
treatment-naive setting, but this was significantly less frequent after subsequent

219
00:13:20.912 --> 00:13:24.552
EGFR TKI therapy. In addition, EGFR mutations

220
00:13:24.592 --> 00:13:28.472
commonly co-occurred with cell cycle alterations throughout therapeutic settings.

221
00:13:29.102 --> 00:13:32.892
And in terms of off-target resistance, MET amplifications, which can be

222
00:13:32.932 --> 00:13:36.902
technically challenging to capture by liquid biopsy, were frequently detected

223
00:13:36.972 --> 00:13:40.892
after first-line EGFR TKI therapy, as were alterations in the

224
00:13:40.932 --> 00:13:44.512
PI3K pathway. Oncogenic alterations in the RAS

225
00:13:44.552 --> 00:13:48.222
pathway, including the actionable BRAP V600E alteration,

226
00:13:48.772 --> 00:13:50.802
were captured across lines of therapy.

227
00:13:51.552 --> 00:13:55.372
And this really highlights the value of liquid biopsy for characterizing drivers

228
00:13:55.432 --> 00:13:59.252
of therapy resistance and enabling informed decision-making in the

229
00:13:59.272 --> 00:14:01.552
clinical setting at the time of disease progression.

230
00:14:02.912 --> 00:14:05.952
Similarly, as a proportion of the total number of co-mutations,

231
00:14:06.352 --> 00:14:10.292
PI3K pathway alterations were commonly detected after first and second-line

232
00:14:10.332 --> 00:14:14.102
therapy, whereas RAS pathway alterations also spanned later lines of

233
00:14:14.172 --> 00:14:17.892
therapy. And this finding is highlighting both shared and distinct

234
00:14:18.032 --> 00:14:21.432
activation of signaling pathways and cancer hallmarks in the

235
00:14:21.472 --> 00:14:25.072
development of acquired therapeutic resistance that drive cancer cell fitness

236
00:14:25.672 --> 00:14:29.612
um, and highlight the value of plasma germline profiling for characterizing

237
00:14:29.952 --> 00:14:33.712
what is driving resistance to EGFR TKI therapy over multiple

238
00:14:33.772 --> 00:14:34.692
lines of therapy.

239
00:14:36.302 --> 00:14:40.041
So to conclude, plasma germline profiling identifies actionable alterations and

240
00:14:40.092 --> 00:14:43.452
uniquely informs management of patients with non-small cell lung cancer,

241
00:14:43.972 --> 00:14:47.852
helping match patients to genotype-targeted therapies that confer a clear survival

242
00:14:47.972 --> 00:14:51.672
benefit. PCGP informs serial clinical decisions with

243
00:14:51.792 --> 00:14:55.592
rapid turnaround time and high feasibility while more optimally capturing

244
00:14:55.612 --> 00:14:57.472
tumor heterogeneity and evolution.

245
00:14:58.172 --> 00:15:01.862
PCGP at the time of disease progression identified actionable drivers of

246
00:15:01.912 --> 00:15:05.592
resistance enabling therapeutic intervention, and in patients with

247
00:15:05.632 --> 00:15:09.372
EGFR-driven non-small cell lung cancer, liquid biopsy captured differential

248
00:15:09.392 --> 00:15:13.352
activation of cancer hallmarks and resistance pathways depending on therapeutic

249
00:15:13.372 --> 00:15:16.981
context and line of therapy. And I'm happy to announce that the full

250
00:15:17.012 --> 00:15:20.572
manuscript is being concurrently published with this presentation in "Cancer

251
00:15:20.612 --> 00:15:24.552
Research Communications," and you can access the full manuscript at the embedded QR

252
00:15:24.592 --> 00:15:24.832
code.

