Thank you for your attention, and I look forward to your questions.

259
00:15:55.332 --> 00:15:56.592
We have time for questions.

260
00:16:05.012 --> 00:16:08.972
Great talk. I was just curious, like for MET and some of the other

261
00:16:09.052 --> 00:16:10.512
ones that you could look in the tissue,

262
00:16:11.352 --> 00:16:14.072
how did you guys look at concordance between

263
00:16:15.092 --> 00:16:17.252
at time of resistance between blood and tumor?

264
00:16:17.812 --> 00:16:20.252
Yeah, we did. And so this is a great question because as you mentioned, MET

265
00:16:20.272 --> 00:16:23.602
amplifications can be technically challenging to capture by liquid biopsy.

266
00:16:24.062 --> 00:16:27.872
And so there were about 79 cases of liquid biopsy at the time of

267
00:16:27.912 --> 00:16:31.712
disease progression after TKI therapy, and we did capture in about

268
00:16:31.752 --> 00:16:34.912
10% of those cases MET amplification with liquid biopsy.

269
00:16:35.332 --> 00:16:38.972
And so in some cases with concurrent tissue biopsy and liquid biopsy,

270
00:16:39.452 --> 00:16:43.172
we were not able to capture the MET amplification by PCGP, which is potentially

271
00:16:43.192 --> 00:16:47.102
reflecting technical challenges, particularly in the context of low tumor burden or

272
00:16:47.192 --> 00:16:49.252
intrathoracic disease, for example.

273
00:16:49.492 --> 00:16:53.422
So yes, we were able to capture these structural alterations by liquid biopsy, but

274
00:16:53.452 --> 00:16:55.272
there were some instances of discordance.

275
00:16:55.872 --> 00:16:56.372
Great work.

276
00:16:56.592 --> 00:16:56.892
Thank you.

277
00:17:00.212 --> 00:17:02.772
Another questions. Another question.

278
00:17:03.932 --> 00:17:07.672
Did you examine patients treated with immunotherapy and the rate

279
00:17:07.712 --> 00:17:09.912
of therapy guidance in those patients?

280
00:17:10.232 --> 00:17:13.712
Yeah. So there were a few patients where, for example, they would be given

281
00:17:13.752 --> 00:17:16.712
immunotherapy based on an MSI-high score by liquid biopsy.

282
00:17:17.312 --> 00:17:21.242
But generally speaking, our focus was on oncogene-driven non-small cell lung cancer

283
00:17:21.353 --> 00:17:23.932
for which immunotherapy is thought to have somewhat limited efficacy.

284
00:17:26.072 --> 00:17:29.912
Can I ask you one? So how do you envision this approach

285
00:17:30.092 --> 00:17:33.572
in late versus early disease using this liquid

286
00:17:33.592 --> 00:17:34.192
biopsy?

287
00:17:34.332 --> 00:17:37.792
Yeah. So I think the focus of this study was predominantly on these metastatic

288
00:17:37.892 --> 00:17:41.332
cancers where we're able to, particularly in the context of higher circulating

289
00:17:41.452 --> 00:17:44.852
tumor burden, where it may be easier to capture drivers of therapy resistance.

290
00:17:45.412 --> 00:17:49.192
I will say that we are performing a similar analysis on patients managed from

291
00:17:49.332 --> 00:17:53.232
2022 onward, and where potentially PCGP might be used

292
00:17:53.292 --> 00:17:56.712
more in the early-stage setting, it might be used more serially.

293
00:17:56.752 --> 00:18:00.092
So we could try to capture not only what is happening maybe with these early-stage

294
00:18:00.132 --> 00:18:03.872
patients, but also what we're seeing with, for example, fourth-generation EGFR

295
00:18:03.912 --> 00:18:06.732
TKIs or the MET EGFR bispecifics.

296
00:18:07.572 --> 00:18:08.012
Thank you.

297
00:18:10.912 --> 00:18:14.691
And do you think there's a role beyond targeted panels?

298
00:18:16.836 --> 00:18:20.456
Whole genome methylation. Where do you see that

299
00:18:20.856 --> 00:18:22.836
playing a role in this population?

300
00:18:23.156 --> 00:18:26.536
Yeah, it's a great point, and I think this will be at a future area of analysis.

301
00:18:26.636 --> 00:18:30.216
But I think we were focused really on what is the CLIA-approved assays in the

302
00:18:30.276 --> 00:18:34.186
context of non-small cell lung cancer, and think in particular, when you're able to

303
00:18:34.216 --> 00:18:38.146
capture these particular alterations with high depth, if you

304
00:18:38.176 --> 00:18:42.156
don't fix gene panel sequencing, that can lead to, as we were trying to show,

305
00:18:42.376 --> 00:18:44.876
matching to these highly effective genotype-targeted therapies.

306
00:18:45.456 --> 00:18:48.456
But it definitely would be worth exploring and might be an area of follow-up in our

307
00:18:48.836 --> 00:18:52.746
future work to look at, especially as whole genome assays

308
00:18:52.816 --> 00:18:56.336
or methylation assays become CLIA approved in terms of management of

309
00:18:56.376 --> 00:18:59.736
metastatic non-small cell lung cancer, what that clinical utility looks like.

310
00:19:02.936 --> 00:19:03.556
Fantastic.

311
00:19:05.376 --> 00:19:05.916
Thank you.

312
00:19:06.736 --> 00:19:07.116
All right.

313
00:19:07.296 --> 00:19:07.406
Thank you.

314
00:19:07.406 --> 00:19:09.156
Thank you very much.

315
00:19:18.116 --> 00:19:18.856
All right, so

316
00:19:19.775 --> 00:19:22.056
the next talk is going to be...

317
00:19:30.736 --> 00:19:34.716
All right. So the next abstract is going to be presented by Dr. Stabile.

318
00:19:35.096 --> 00:19:38.986
Did I say it correctly? So, and the title of the talk is Feasibility of

319
00:19:38.996 --> 00:19:42.256
Plasma ctDNA for Detecting Brain Metastasis

320
00:19:42.416 --> 00:19:44.616
Specific Alterations in Lung Cancer. Please.

321
00:19:55.446 --> 00:19:59.076
Thank you to the organizers for the opportunity to present our work

322
00:19:59.136 --> 00:20:03.096
today. I'll be discussing the use of plasma

323
00:20:03.196 --> 00:20:06.836
ctDNA to detect brain-specific genomic alterations

324
00:20:07.276 --> 00:20:10.736
with a focus on MET amplifications in lung cancer brain

325
00:20:10.756 --> 00:20:11.636
metastases.

326
00:20:13.176 --> 00:20:14.856
I have no disclosures to report.

327
00:20:16.696 --> 00:20:20.586
Non-small cell lung cancer has the highest frequency of metastasis to the

328
00:20:20.656 --> 00:20:24.276
brain among all solid tumors and is associated with poor

329
00:20:24.375 --> 00:20:25.516
clinical outcomes.

330
00:20:26.796 --> 00:20:30.456
The brain is often the site of disease progression, and after

331
00:20:30.516 --> 00:20:34.336
radiation, there are no effective therapies, and no brain-specific

332
00:20:34.396 --> 00:20:35.956
targeted therapies exist.

333
00:20:36.956 --> 00:20:40.736
Several seminal studies have identified brain metastasis-specific

334
00:20:40.756 --> 00:20:44.376
targetable genomic alterations, highlighting the

335
00:20:44.436 --> 00:20:48.276
need to identify therapeutic targets in brain metastases to improve

336
00:20:48.356 --> 00:20:51.016
outcomes in this challenging patient population.

337
00:20:53.836 --> 00:20:57.656
Our team has had a long-standing interest in the hepatocyte growth factor,

338
00:20:58.016 --> 00:21:01.876
HGF-MET signaling pathway, which is frequently activated in

339
00:21:01.936 --> 00:21:05.656
lung cancer. This can occur through HGF or MET

340
00:21:05.696 --> 00:21:09.196
protein overexpression, MET point mutations,

341
00:21:09.496 --> 00:21:12.976
exon 14 skipping mutations, amplification, and

342
00:21:13.036 --> 00:21:16.256
fusions. All which can increase MET activity.

343
00:21:17.356 --> 00:21:21.036
Importantly, MET alterations are targetable, and we currently have

344
00:21:21.136 --> 00:21:24.996
two FDA-approved MET TKIs, cabmetinib and tepotinib,

345
00:21:25.616 --> 00:21:28.956
with another, selvalinib, on the horizon.

346
00:21:30.096 --> 00:21:33.616
The HGF-MET signaling pathway has also been implicated in brain

347
00:21:33.676 --> 00:21:36.716
metastasis biology. In this regard,

348
00:21:37.236 --> 00:21:40.456
HGF has been shown to be secreted from tumor-associated

349
00:21:40.616 --> 00:21:44.116
astrocytes, and increased phosphorylated MET has been

350
00:21:44.136 --> 00:21:45.776
detected in brain metastases.

351
00:21:47.896 --> 00:21:51.636
In order to further understand the role of MET in lung cancer brain

352
00:21:51.696 --> 00:21:55.336
metastases, we performed MET fluorescence in

353
00:21:55.396 --> 00:21:59.336
situ hybridization in a large cohort of primary

354
00:21:59.436 --> 00:22:02.406
lung adenocarcinomas and brain metastases.

355
00:22:03.756 --> 00:22:07.476
We found that MET amplification, defined by a MET to CEP

356
00:22:07.576 --> 00:22:11.376
ratio greater than two, was significantly

357
00:22:11.536 --> 00:22:14.316
more common in the brain metastases at a rate of

358
00:22:14.356 --> 00:22:18.316
16.4%, compared to only 3.7%

359
00:22:18.496 --> 00:22:19.916
in primary lung tumors.

360
00:22:21.076 --> 00:22:25.026
We also identified a significant enrichment of MET mutations in

361
00:22:25.056 --> 00:22:26.236
the brain metastases.

362
00:22:27.456 --> 00:22:28.786
These MET-amplified

363
00:22:29.676 --> 00:22:33.496
brain tumors are a distinct biological subtype with

364
00:22:33.576 --> 00:22:36.656
unique genomic features, an altered tumor immune

365
00:22:36.736 --> 00:22:40.696
microenvironment, metabolic reprogramming with a reliance on

366
00:22:40.736 --> 00:22:41.706
glycolysis,

367
00:22:42.696 --> 00:22:44.566
and increased EMT signaling.

368
00:22:45.876 --> 00:22:49.566
Although these are associated with poor patient survival, as shown by the

369
00:22:49.636 --> 00:22:49.936
red

370
00:22:51.556 --> 00:22:55.456
line and the survival curve, MET-amplified brain

371
00:22:55.616 --> 00:22:59.156
metastases do respond to MET TKIs in preclinical

372
00:22:59.236 --> 00:23:02.796
models, and clinical activity has been

373
00:23:02.816 --> 00:23:06.476
reported in several patient case

374
00:23:06.556 --> 00:23:07.156
reports.

375
00:23:08.556 --> 00:23:12.416
MET amplification is therefore a clinically meaningful example

376
00:23:12.476 --> 00:23:16.016
of the molecular divergence between primary lung tumors and brain

377
00:23:16.056 --> 00:23:20.036
metastases, and this divergence highlights the need

378
00:23:20.496 --> 00:23:24.456
for non-invasive approaches to detect this brain-specific MET

379
00:23:24.536 --> 00:23:27.916
amplification to identify patients who may benefit from

380
00:23:27.956 --> 00:23:29.416
MET-targeted therapies.

381
00:23:32.936 --> 00:23:36.676
Even though while blood-based ctDNA

382
00:23:36.916 --> 00:23:40.876
sensitivity for brain metastases is known to be limited,

383
00:23:41.396 --> 00:23:45.256
we hypothesized that MET alterations detected in ctDNA

384
00:23:45.296 --> 00:23:48.056
would be found more often in patients with brain

385
00:23:48.076 --> 00:23:51.496
metastases. Using a retrospective cohort of

386
00:23:51.536 --> 00:23:55.456
metastatic non-small cell lung cancer patients that underwent standard of care

387
00:23:55.616 --> 00:23:59.356
ctDNA testing with the Guardant 360 platform at our

388
00:23:59.376 --> 00:24:03.156
institution, we evaluated the presence of brain metastases

389
00:24:03.236 --> 00:24:04.456
on MRI scans.

390
00:24:05.596 --> 00:24:08.636
We found that MET alterations detected by

391
00:24:08.696 --> 00:24:12.576
ctDNA were significantly more common in patients

392
00:24:12.696 --> 00:24:16.636
with brain metastases than those without, and this was driven

393
00:24:16.676 --> 00:24:19.116
by MET amplification, not MET

394
00:24:19.176 --> 00:24:22.664
mutations.This supports the potential of

395
00:24:22.724 --> 00:24:25.924
ctDNA as a non-invasive method for detecting brain

396
00:24:25.944 --> 00:24:28.534
metastasis-specific MET amplification.

397
00:24:30.644 --> 00:24:34.484
To prospectively test this, we analyzed pre

398
00:24:34.494 --> 00:24:38.364
and post-craniotomy plasma samples, along with matched brain

399
00:24:38.404 --> 00:24:42.204
metastasis tissue from patients with metastatic non-small cell

400
00:24:42.264 --> 00:24:45.244
lung cancer undergoing surgery for symptomatic brain

401
00:24:45.284 --> 00:24:48.654
lesions. Twenty-eight patients were included in this

402
00:24:48.744 --> 00:24:52.624
study. Peripheral blood was

403
00:24:52.724 --> 00:24:56.344
collected pre-surgery at day zero, referred to as P1

404
00:24:56.404 --> 00:25:00.084
plasma, and post-surgery prior to systemic therapy

405
00:25:00.164 --> 00:25:02.784
initiation, referred to as P2 plasma.

406
00:25:03.924 --> 00:25:07.784
Brain metastasis tissue was collected at the time of surgery and prepared as

407
00:25:07.944 --> 00:25:09.164
FFPE blocks.

408
00:25:09.984 --> 00:25:13.624
Samples were sequenced using the Predicinn CARE 200 gene

409
00:25:13.724 --> 00:25:17.474
NGS assay and analyzed using Predicinn's DeepSeek

410
00:25:17.584 --> 00:25:19.144
bioinformatics pipeline.

411
00:25:20.264 --> 00:25:24.064
After excluding cases for insufficient viable tumor, low

412
00:25:24.144 --> 00:25:27.384
tumor fraction, or failed QC, we

413
00:25:27.464 --> 00:25:31.124
analyzed 13 complete sets, three partial

414
00:25:31.204 --> 00:25:34.804
sets of tissue in P1 plasma only, and seven

415
00:25:34.964 --> 00:25:38.544
tissue-only samples, for a total of 23 brain metastasis

416
00:25:38.584 --> 00:25:39.154
samples.

417
00:25:40.104 --> 00:25:43.544
We asked if alterations detected in ctDNA at baseline were

418
00:25:43.624 --> 00:25:47.004
absent or reduced in post-craniotomy ctDNA,

419
00:25:47.644 --> 00:25:51.604
and if brain met specific alterations found in the tumor tissue could also

420
00:25:51.684 --> 00:25:53.424
be detected in ctDNA.

421
00:25:55.804 --> 00:25:59.074
This slide depicts the molecular landscape of lung cancer brain

422
00:25:59.124 --> 00:26:02.984
metastases in our cohort. The most common alterations

423
00:26:03.484 --> 00:26:05.864
were TP53, RB1,

424
00:26:06.404 --> 00:26:09.764
CDK2A and 2B, and PIK3CA,

425
00:26:10.724 --> 00:26:13.504
each present in more than half of the samples.

426
00:26:14.444 --> 00:26:18.384
Additionally, clinically actionable alterations including the

427
00:26:18.444 --> 00:26:21.864
classical EGFR TKI sensitizing mutations,

428
00:26:22.864 --> 00:26:26.804
as well as the targetable KRAS G12C mutation, were

429
00:26:26.864 --> 00:26:28.644
each detected in three patients.

430
00:26:29.524 --> 00:26:33.404
And relevant to our research interests, MET amplification was

431
00:26:33.424 --> 00:26:36.284
detected in six out of 23 patients, or

432
00:26:36.504 --> 00:26:40.484
26%, consistent with the findings

433
00:26:40.784 --> 00:26:44.284
that I reported in our earlier cohort of close to 200

434
00:26:44.344 --> 00:26:44.964
cases.

435
00:26:48.264 --> 00:26:52.064
While many alterations were shared between the brain

436
00:26:52.104 --> 00:26:55.964
metastasis tissue and the two plasma samples, complete

437
00:26:56.024 --> 00:26:59.544
loss of an alteration in the P2 plasma that was

438
00:26:59.584 --> 00:27:03.144
detected in both the P1 plasma and the brain tissue

439
00:27:03.564 --> 00:27:07.164
was rare, occurring in only one of 13 patients,

440
00:27:07.784 --> 00:27:10.784
and this was the loss of an EGFR amplification.

441
00:27:11.924 --> 00:27:15.224
However, a decrease of more than 50% variant allele

442
00:27:15.324 --> 00:27:19.044
frequency was seen for multiple variants in an additional 12 of

443
00:27:19.104 --> 00:27:22.504
13 patients, despite similar percent tumor

444
00:27:22.584 --> 00:27:26.484
fractions, suggesting that ctDNA shed from brain metastases

445
00:27:26.604 --> 00:27:27.444
is possible.

446
00:27:28.904 --> 00:27:31.484
Notably, amplifications or deletions in

447
00:27:31.544 --> 00:27:34.944
CDK2A or B, KEAP1, and

448
00:27:35.084 --> 00:27:38.964
NF1 were only detected in the brain tissue, and

449
00:27:39.004 --> 00:27:42.424
only one of two MET amplifications were

450
00:27:42.464 --> 00:27:46.224
detected in the plasma in the complete sets, and one of

451
00:27:46.304 --> 00:27:48.304
six when we included all patients.

452
00:27:51.664 --> 00:27:55.264
One particularly interesting case involved a patient who

453
00:27:55.284 --> 00:27:59.024
received five fractions of postoperative brain

454
00:27:59.064 --> 00:28:02.784
radiation therapy to the tumor bed, ending just one day

455
00:28:02.864 --> 00:28:05.024
before the P2 sample collection.

456
00:28:05.944 --> 00:28:07.184
In the P2 plasma,

457
00:28:08.104 --> 00:28:11.824
we identified MET and MYC

458
00:28:11.884 --> 00:28:15.104
amplifications and a TP53 deletion.

459
00:28:15.124 --> 00:28:18.704
These were present in the brain metastasis tissue, but were

460
00:28:18.804 --> 00:28:21.244
absent in the P1 ctDNA

461
00:28:21.284 --> 00:28:24.993
sample. We also compared the variant allele

462
00:28:25.104 --> 00:28:28.944
frequencies and CNVs between P1 and P2 in

463
00:28:28.984 --> 00:28:29.724
this patient.

464
00:28:30.724 --> 00:28:34.394
Across the board, as you can see in this heat map, VAFs and

465
00:28:34.444 --> 00:28:36.824
CNVs were increased in the P2

466
00:28:38.284 --> 00:28:39.564
plasma collection.

467
00:28:40.684 --> 00:28:44.664
And the majority of the alterations highlighted here in

468
00:28:44.724 --> 00:28:48.504
red were increased more than we would have expected based on the tumor

469
00:28:48.604 --> 00:28:49.164
fraction.

470
00:28:50.104 --> 00:28:53.664
This suggests that radiation therapy may enhance tumor DNA

471
00:28:53.744 --> 00:28:57.664
shedding, potentially improving ctDNA detection of

472
00:28:57.784 --> 00:28:59.624
brain-specific alterations.

473
00:29:01.724 --> 00:29:05.404
To summarize, molecular divergence between primary lung

474
00:29:05.444 --> 00:29:08.844
tumors and brain metastases highlights the need for

475
00:29:08.884 --> 00:29:12.844
non-invasive detection of brain metastasis-specific

476
00:29:12.884 --> 00:29:16.804
genomic alterations, and MET amplification

477
00:29:16.844 --> 00:29:20.524
is a good example of this. Brain met specific

478
00:29:20.604 --> 00:29:24.234
alterations can be detected in plasma ctDNA, but

479
00:29:24.284 --> 00:29:26.964
sensitivity still remains a major limitation.

480
00:29:28.304 --> 00:29:32.134
Improved detection will require assays with greater sensitivity

481
00:29:32.244 --> 00:29:36.164
and optimized collection timing, such as the example that I showed

482
00:29:36.264 --> 00:29:39.784
with post-radiation therapy, and this will be essential to

483
00:29:39.844 --> 00:29:41.864
improve yield and clinical utility.

484
00:29:42.984 --> 00:29:46.624
To our knowledge, this is the only study to date that uses matched

485
00:29:46.724 --> 00:29:50.304
pre and post-craniotomy plasma and paired brain MET tissue,

486
00:29:51.424 --> 00:29:55.264
allowing us to directly evaluate ctDNA detection of

487
00:29:55.284 --> 00:29:56.924
brain-specific alterations.

488
00:29:58.044 --> 00:30:01.744
Our ongoing studies include optimizing sampling windows and

489
00:30:01.824 --> 00:30:05.644
assay sensitivity in both plasma and CSF,

490
00:30:06.224 --> 00:30:08.913
and integrating this with radiogenomic modeling.

491
00:30:11.884 --> 00:30:15.804
Finally, I would like to acknowledge our team and collaborators that contributed to

492
00:30:15.874 --> 00:30:19.444
this work at the University of Pittsburgh Hillman Cancer Center,

493
00:30:20.044 --> 00:30:23.924
The James at The Ohio State University, and our industry

494
00:30:24.044 --> 00:30:27.848
partners at Predicinn.As well as our funding sources

495
00:30:27.968 --> 00:30:31.888
and most importantly, the patients and families who made this study possible.

496
00:30:32.488 --> 00:30:32.847
Thank you.

497
00:30:38.668 --> 00:30:41.968
Thank you very much. So we have time for some questions.

498
00:30:49.108 --> 00:30:49.928
Is this on? Yeah.

499
00:30:50.788 --> 00:30:54.028
Very nice talk. Thank you. Barbara Zientek of FireBio. I have a quick question.

500
00:30:54.088 --> 00:30:57.988
Do you think that that post-radiotherapy signal could be

501
00:30:58.048 --> 00:31:00.648
contributed if something changes with the blood-brain barrier?

502
00:31:01.828 --> 00:31:03.708
That's our hypothesis, yes.

